We can see the SalesPrice resembels a log normal distribution: Thus, if the random variable X is log-normally distributed, then Y = ln(X) has a normal distribution.[Wiki]¶

Because of this we will do a log transform on SalePrice¶

We are going to assume that for some the missing values like those in PoolQC are because there is no pool present for the house in question. Therefore we will set these values to none.

Other variables like LotFrontage which cannot be zero will need to be repaced with the mode.

Sometimes the mode will be based on houses with similar features such as those form the same Neighborhood, yearbuilt, or has Central Air as a way to make a more educated guess at what the value might be.

def boxstats(data):
    '''Returns a prineted out summary of boxplot stats including max, min, mean, whisker values, nearest data points inside
        whiskers and number of data pointsouside the whisker values
        
        Call boxstatsarr() to get values returned in array form] '''
    values=data.sort_values()
    minimum=values.iloc[0] ###### we must use iloc or else it uses the original index from the df and .sort would do nothing
    maximum=values.iloc[(len(values)-1)] 
    Q1=values.iloc[int((0.25*len(values)))]#must cast to an int or: Cannot index by location index with a non-integer key
    Q2=values.iloc[int(0.50*len(values))]
    Q3=values.iloc[int(0.75*len(values))]
    LW=int(Q1-1.5*(Q3-Q1))#2-1  must select nearest point within this range to properly set whisker !!!!!!!!!!!
    UW=int(Q3+1.5*(Q3-Q1))#3-2
    LWP=values.array[np.searchsorted(values, LW, side='Left')]    
    UWP=values.array[np.searchsorted(values, UW, side='Right')-1]# is left correct?
   # indexmax=[np.searchsorted(values, UW, side='Left')-1]
#abs(data-LW).argmin
    #LWf = np.abs(values - LW).argmin()
    tolow=int((np.searchsorted(values, LW, side='Left')))
    tohigh=int(len(values)-(np.searchsorted(values, UW, side='Right')))
    
    mean=int(sum(values)/len(values))#this includes our outliers in the mean
    nullcount=data.isnull().sum()
    dist=data.nunique()
    print('min {} \nL-whisker: {} \nLowestinsidewhisker: {} \nQ1  {} \nQ2  {} \nQ3  {} \nmax {}\nU-whisker is {} \nhighestsinsidewhisker is {}\nmean is {}\nwe have {} values below whiskers and {} above \nThere are {} null values \nthere are {} distinct values'.format(minimum,LW,LWP,Q1,Q2,Q3,maximum,UW,UWP,mean,tolow,tohigh,nullcount,dist))
    #return [LW,minimum,Q1,Q2,Q3,maximum,UW]
   # argmin()

def QuickJab(whatdata,ylab):
    '''QuickLook(whatdata,ylab):  sns.boxplot(y=whatdata,color='Yellow')
    returns yellow boxplot with black swarmoverlay
    
    example: QuickJab(train['SalePrice'],'SalePrice') 
   
  '''
    sns.boxplot(y=whatdata,color='Yellow')
    #ax=sns.swarmplot(y=whatdata,color='black')
    ax=sns.violinplot(y=whatdata,color='black') #use violin plot as swarm plot it to intensive
    ax.set_ylabel(ylab,fontsize=40)
    boxstats(whatdata)

def boxstatsarr(data):
    '''Returns array summary of boxplot values [LW,minimum,Q1,Q2,Q3,maximum,UW)] 
    
     Returns a prineted out summary of boxplot stats including max, min, mean, whisker values, nearest data points inside
        whiskers and number of data pointsouside the whisker values
        
        Call boxstats() to get printed summary of stats] '''
    
    values=train[train['YearBuilt']==1880]['SalePrice']
    values=data.sort_values()
    minimum=int(values.iloc[0]) #we must use iloc or else it uses the original index from the df and .sort would do nothing
    maximum=values.iloc[(len(values)-1)]
    Q1=values.iloc[int((0.25*len(values)))]#must cast to an int or: Cannot index by location index with a non-integer key
    Q2=values.iloc[int(0.50*len(values))]
    Q3=values.iloc[int(0.75*len(values))]
    LW=int(Q1-1.5*(Q3-Q1))#2-1  must select nearest point within this range to properly set whisker !!!!!!!!!!!
    UW=int(Q3+1.5*(Q3-Q1))#3-2
    
                                                                    #numpy.searchsorted(a, v, side='left', sorter=None)
                                                                    #Find the indices into a sorted array a such that, if the 
                                                                    #corresponding elements in v were# inserted before the 
                                                                    #indices, the order of a would be preserved.
    LWP=values.array[np.searchsorted(values, LW, side='Left')]     ##note ##side	returned index i satisfies
    UWP=values.array[np.searchsorted(values, UW, side='Right')-1]     #left	a[i-1] < v <= a[i]
                                                                        #right	a[i-1] <= v < a[i]
    mean=int(sum(values)/len(values))
    
    tolow=int((np.searchsorted(values, LW, side='Left')))
    tohigh=int(len(values)-(np.searchsorted(values, UW, side='Right')))
    
#abs(data-LW).argmin
    #LWf = np.abs(values - LW).argmin()
    
    
    #if you're going to perform arithmetic functions to your lists, you should really be using arrays instead. 
    from numpy import array
    boxstatarr=array([minimum,LW,LWP,Q1,Q2,Q3,maximum,UW,UWP,mean,tolow,tohigh])
    return boxstatarr
